    pearls: ["The hallmark of intracranial hypotension is ORTHOSTATIC HEADACHE: headache that worsens within 15 minutes of being upright and improves within 15-30 minutes of lying flat -- this postural component distinguishes it from other headache types","PDPH prevention: use the SMALLEST gauge needle that is clinically appropriate; use pencil-point (Whitacre/Sprotte) rather than cutting-tip (Quincke) needles for spinal procedures; orient the bevel parallel to the longitudinal dural fibers","Epidural blood patch (EBP) is the definitive treatment for PDPH: 15-30 mL of autologous blood injected into the epidural space seals the dural defect; 70-90% success with first patch; offer if conservative measures fail after 24-48 hours or for severe symptoms","A headache that starts as orthostatic (positional) but becomes CONSTANT and non-positional should raise concern for subdural hematoma -- chronic brain sagging stretches and tears bridging veins; order urgent CT head","CN VI (abducens nerve) palsy causing DIPLOPIA is the most common cranial nerve deficit in intracranial hypotension because it has the longest intracranial course and is most susceptible to traction from brain sagging","CSF rhinorrhea or otorrhea after head trauma requires urgent evaluation: test fluid for beta-2 transferrin (specific to CSF); risk of ascending bacterial meningitis through the skull base defect; keep HOB elevated 30 degrees, avoid nose-blowing/straining"],
