    pearls: ["Ferritin is the SINGLE BEST test for diagnosing iron deficiency: <30 ng/mL = diagnostic (sensitivity 92%, specificity 98%); <15 ng/mL = definitive; in inflammatory states where ferritin is falsely elevated, use ferritin <100 ng/mL with TSAT <20% as the diagnostic threshold","IDA iron study pattern: LOW ferritin, LOW serum iron, HIGH TIBC, LOW TSAT (<20%); contrast with ACD: normal/HIGH ferritin, LOW serum iron, LOW/normal TIBC, LOW TSAT -- the key differentiator is ferritin and TIBC","All men and postmenopausal women with new IDA must be evaluated for GI malignancy with upper endoscopy and colonoscopy -- colon cancer can present as occult blood loss causing IDA before any GI symptoms appear","The sTfR/log ferritin index >2 is the best test to distinguish IDA from ACD in patients with concurrent inflammation (sTfR is elevated in IDA because iron-starved erythroid precursors upregulate transferrin receptors, but sTfR is normal in ACD where inflammation, not iron deficiency, suppresses erythropoiesis)","Oral iron absorption occurs primarily in the DUODENUM and requires ACIDIC pH (gastric acid converts insoluble Fe3+ to soluble Fe2+); PPIs, H2 blockers, and antacids reduce absorption by raising gastric pH; vitamin C enhances absorption by providing a reducing environment","Continue oral iron for 3-6 MONTHS AFTER hemoglobin normalizes to fully replenish iron stores (target ferritin >50-100 ng/mL); stopping when hemoglobin normalizes results in relapse because stores remain depleted"],
